            "views": [
                { "type": "text", "text": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:700;font-style:italic;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The Floating Piers<\/span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;was a temporary,&nbsp;<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Site-specific_art\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">site-specific<\/span><\/a><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;work of art by&nbsp;<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Christo_and_Jeanne-Claude\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Christo and Jeanne-Claude<\/span><\/a><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">, installed in 2016 at&nbsp;<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lake_Iseo\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Lake Iseo<\/span><\/a><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">. The iconic installation was visited by over 1.5 million people for the period of 16 days. Yellow fabric created a walkable surface between&nbsp;<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sulzano\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Sulzano<\/span><\/a><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">,&nbsp;<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Monte_Isola\" style=\"text-decoration:none;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Monte Isola<\/span><\/a><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;and the island of San Paolo. The floating pathway was with a total area of 100,000 sqm. Regardless of its short duration the event generated enormous public interest and boosted the local economy of the small town of Sulzano.<\/span><\/p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">To commemorate this event the local government opened a contest for a pavilion proposal on a specific site in Sulzano. This project looks at various aspects and inspects in detail the urban fabric of the small town. Aiming to create a series of points within the city that act as a public space network for tourists to explore. The internal web of temporary exhibitions points have double purpose varying seasonally. A set of furniture pieces were designed and a plan for creating continuous saffron-colored strips guiding visitors through the city.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>" },
                { "type": "grid", "content": [
                    ["/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/M1.jpg", "/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/M2.jpg", "/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/M3.jpg"]
                ]},
                { "type": "text", "text": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The proposal for the cultural development of the area is developed in multiple parts. The main event is proposed to take place in the lake for several weeks during spring every two years. Making it possible for artists to take advantage of the amazing opportunity and sculpt an experience in the lake. Lake Iseo is the fourth largest lake in Lombardy, Italy, fed by the Oglio river. It has an area of&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#222222;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">65.3 km&sup2; which can host various smaller or bigger land art installations. Connection to the island within the lake or the villages surrounding it can be created following the example set by Christo, but the space allows freedom for exploration and interpretation.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>" },
                { "type": "grid", "content": [
                    ["/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/S1.jpg", "/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/S2.jpg", "/dna/media/projects/sulzano/content/S3.jpg"]
                ]},
                { "type": "text", "text": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The network of pathways with colored continuous lines leads up the hill into an open pavilion blending into the slope.The architectural proposal is minimal overhanging concrete structure resembling the outline of two boxes one on top of the other that are slightly rotated and form a continuous line. Blending into the landscape with three concrete slabs creating two floors hold big exhibition areas and stunning views towards the lake. &nbsp;The space manifests itself as a playground for art and culture where the iconic event can be commemorated. The pavilion has two levels with distinct spatial programs that can vary depending on the season or during events.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n<p><br><\/p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:12pt;margin-bottom:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:10pt;font-family:Arial;color:#434343;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:italic;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The space was designed in 2016 for the Comune di Sulzano, Italy.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>" }
            ]
        },
